{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.3,0.51,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112164"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/767"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94229"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9101"},{"type":"tags","id":"9207"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45409"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112164"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset severe upper abdominal pain which has now spread over his entire abdomen. He has never experienced pain like this before. He has a medical history of hypertension. His only regular medication is ramipril. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks three cans of beer daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and is sweating profusely. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is rigidity in the epigastrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior myocardial infarction","Biliary colic","Acute pancreatitis","Perforated peptic ulcer","Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms highly suggestive of a perforated gut viscus, with \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforated peptic ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E being the most likely diagnosis. The sudden onset of severe upper abdominal pain that rapidly spreads throughout the abdomen is characteristic of peritoneal irritation caused by leakage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. The presence of epigastric rigidity on examination further supports this diagnosis. Whilst dyspeptic symptoms often precede perforation, this is not aways the case. Similarly, widespread peritonitis does not accompany all cases and localised, contained perforation is well recognised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause sudden, severe abdominal pain. However, this patient\u0027s blood pressure is normal, which is atypical for a ruptured aneurysm where hypotension would be expected due to significant blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E can sometimes present with upper abdominal pain, but it would be unusual for it to spread throughout the abdomen or cause epigastric rigidity. Additionally, the patient\u0027s vital signs are relatively stable, which is less consistent with an acute myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes right upper quadrant or epigastric pain, but it does not usually spread throughout the abdomen. The pain is often colicky rather than constant, and while the patient may be uncomfortable, they typically do not appear as unwell as this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause severe upper abdominal pain, but it usually does not spread as rapidly throughout the abdomen. While it should always be considered in the differential diagnosis of acute upper abdominal pain, the sudden onset and spread of pain, along with the epigastric rigidity, are more consistent with a perforated peptic ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that not all patients with peptic ulcer complications have preceding dyspeptic symptoms. About 10% of cases may present with a complication such as bleeding or perforation without prior symptoms. The patient\u0027s history of smoking and alcohol consumption are risk factors for peptic ulcer disease. Prompt diagnosis and management are crucial in cases of perforated peptic ulcer to prevent complications such as sepsis and peritonitis. If there is any diagnostic doubt, imaging studies could be performed, looking for free intraperitoneal gas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden onset of upper abdominal pain spreading throughout the abdomen is highly suggestive of a perforated gut viscus.","Perforated peptic ulcer can present without preceding dyspeptic symptoms in about 10% of cases.","Rigidity in the epigastrium is a key physical examination finding in perforated peptic ulcer."],"references":["Lanas A, Chan FKL. Peptic ulcer disease. Lancet. 2017;390:613-24. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)32404-7/abstract","Soreide K, Thorsen K, Harrison EM, et al. Perforated peptic ulcer. Lancet. 2015:26;386: 1288\u201398. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(15)00276-7/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94229"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94229"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T09:29:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T09:29:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"767"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112164"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"em